WEBVTT

00:00.130 --> 00:14.162
Good to see everybody this morning really excited to jump into part two of our series called Finding Your Sweet Spot and we're talking about how to escape the hustle and embrace

00:14.306 --> 00:15.287
generosity.

00:15.468 --> 00:19.113
And if you weren't with us last week, you've got to go back and check out part one.

00:19.213 --> 00:21.256
Each of these parts build on one another.

00:21.296 --> 00:24.761
And last week we had a conversation that's at the heart of all of this.

00:25.161 --> 00:27.485
It's the sweet spot of contentment.

00:27.565 --> 00:32.371
When we escape the hustle and embrace generosity and find contentment in our lives.

00:32.452 --> 00:39.922
And what we looked at last week is that contentment isn't found in having more, but it's found in trusting that God is enough.

00:40.066 --> 00:42.169
It's not in accumulation, accumulation.

00:42.269 --> 00:45.914
Often, culture would teach us the more we have, the more content will be.

00:46.655 --> 00:50.120
But we talked last week about, but where is the line of enough?

00:50.741 --> 00:55.588
And what happens if we trust God to be enough in the midst of our lives?

00:55.648 --> 01:01.556
Now, a part of contentment and a part of this whole conversation is all about money.

01:01.817 --> 01:08.306
And I know some of you, you might be here for the very first time and you're like, oh my gosh, this is exactly what I expected.

01:08.802 --> 01:10.324
The pastor's going to talk about money.

01:10.524 --> 01:12.767
They're probably going to pass an offering plate around.

01:12.808 --> 01:14.330
I know exactly what's going to happen.

01:14.670 --> 01:15.251
And I get that.

01:15.331 --> 01:18.175
I get that might be a stereotype you're coming with.

01:18.556 --> 01:24.464
But here at Connexis, we want to talk about all the topics of our lives, including our finances.

01:24.524 --> 01:29.010
And I want you to know, this is a shame-free, guilt-free conversation.

01:29.186 --> 01:32.171
that we've all made mistakes when it comes to finances.

01:32.231 --> 01:36.578
There are things that we all wish that we've done differently or things that we want to change.

01:36.859 --> 01:40.364
And the goal today isn't manipulation, it's invitation for you.

01:40.945 --> 01:42.788
And I just want you to sit back and listen.

01:43.389 --> 01:44.811
And it's a family conversation.

01:44.872 --> 01:52.804
So if you're here today and you would say, hey, I don't actually regularly call Connects' home, then we're kind of having a family convo today about all this.

01:52.845 --> 01:56.210
So you get to sit around the table and listen to the conversation.

01:56.258 --> 02:01.565
And we're really, really glad that you're here because money plays an important part of our lives, right?

02:03.108 --> 02:04.289
You know why we talk about money?

02:04.349 --> 02:06.272
Because I know you're talking about money, right?

02:06.352 --> 02:10.237
You talk about your house, and it's an important conversation for us all to have.

02:10.858 --> 02:15.264
Now, last week, part of what we looked at was this verse that Jesus teaches us.

02:15.285 --> 02:19.430
It says, where your treasure is, there your heart will be also.

02:19.751 --> 02:24.978
Another way of saying this is, your money is the steering wheel for your heart.

02:25.378 --> 02:30.625
And to me, this is such a powerful concept if you can get your head around it.

02:31.026 --> 02:38.356
And the reason is, if you know what the steering wheel is, it means that you can steer your car where you want it to go, right?

02:38.396 --> 02:43.103
If I put you in a car and you couldn't find the steering wheel, you would probably panic, right?

02:43.223 --> 02:44.224
Where am I going to go?

02:44.244 --> 02:47.108
What country am I in that they don't have steering wheels in their cars?

02:47.409 --> 02:54.098
Or if you've ever been in a self-driving car, they have them in California, nothing will make you more anxious than a car that is driving itself.

02:54.882 --> 03:00.230
But if you can find the steering wheel, man, you can leverage it to go where you wanna go.

03:00.270 --> 03:01.833
And that's the question I wanna ask today.

03:02.153 --> 03:09.945
How, how do you leverage your money to grow greater trust and greater freedom in your relationship with God?

03:10.546 --> 03:18.799
How can you leverage your money to grow your heart for God, to grow the freedom in your life, to grow the trust in your life, to grow the contentment in your life?

03:18.839 --> 03:20.562
That's what I wanna look at today.

03:20.994 --> 03:25.215
And what I want to do is I want to start with an account of Jesus.

03:25.316 --> 03:27.346
Jesus is hanging out at the temple.

03:27.522 --> 03:28.783
with his disciples.

03:29.324 --> 03:32.487
And what's happening is it's the busiest part of the temple.

03:32.647 --> 03:34.409
And they've got different things you can do there.

03:34.669 --> 03:35.710
This is in the Old Testament.

03:35.730 --> 03:37.692
You could offer sacrifices for your sins.

03:37.732 --> 03:38.633
There's few things.

03:38.773 --> 03:41.916
And there's this place where people would give financially.

03:42.376 --> 03:47.581
And they actually had 13 places where you could put your money.

03:47.602 --> 03:49.303
They were like upside down trumpets.

03:49.323 --> 03:51.906
They were either brass or copper or metal.

03:52.606 --> 03:56.370
And what would happen was they were standing there watching people

03:56.610 --> 04:01.383
put financial gifts inside these upside-down trumpets.

04:01.403 --> 04:04.131
And they had a better name, I'm sure, but that's what we're calling them for today, okay?

04:04.693 --> 04:05.294
And it says this.

04:06.056 --> 04:08.744
Well, Jesus says, well, Jesus was in the temple.

04:08.804 --> 04:12.434
He watched the rich people dropping their gifts

04:12.706 --> 04:14.328
in the collection box, right?

04:14.368 --> 04:23.001
You can hear that, the crash, they would be coming with a bags maybe of money, coins, big pocketfuls, and it was kind of a show.

04:23.041 --> 04:29.591
They wanted people to know how much they were giving, and so they might give like an all 13 trumpets, they'd just crash, crash, crash.

04:29.932 --> 04:33.437
Like people go, ooh, look at that guy, he's giving a lot of money, it's so loud, right?

04:35.139 --> 04:42.290
It says this, then a poor widow came by and dropped in two small coins, two pennies.

04:43.842 --> 04:46.285
Plink, plink.

04:48.287 --> 04:49.709
And I can hear disciples going on.

04:51.171 --> 04:53.494
I don't know, those rich guys see what they dropped in.

04:53.514 --> 04:55.476
And Jesus says this, I tell you the truth.

04:56.337 --> 05:10.674
Jesus said, this poor widow has given more than all the rest of them, for they have given a tiny part of their surplus, but she, poor as she is, has given everything that she has.

05:12.034 --> 05:30.523
that when you look around this temple and you see all these people around, if you wanna know who's truly living in freedom, if you wanna know who's truly trusting God, if you wanna know who truly has likely the greatest prayer life in this entire place, it's this widow.

05:31.825 --> 05:33.288
This is the one that you need to look at.

05:33.488 --> 05:37.394
This is the one who is clearly honoring me.

05:38.946 --> 05:42.591
When I was a kid, I grew up at a church of about 80 people.

05:43.612 --> 05:49.160
And when you're like 10 or 12 years old, there's a fast leadership pipeline there.

05:49.681 --> 05:52.084
And I remember at 12 years old, they're like, oh, you're 12 years old?

05:52.104 --> 05:53.806
You're going to start taking up the offering.

05:54.467 --> 05:58.993
And the offering was these little metal plates that you would hand around to take up the offering.

05:59.254 --> 06:01.757
In the middle of the service, you'd walk down the aisles and hand them out.

06:02.659 --> 06:08.146
And what people probably didn't think about was it would be me and an adult

06:08.770 --> 06:13.555
And what a lot of people didn't think about was after the service, we also were the ones who counted all the money.

06:14.576 --> 06:20.982
And so at 12 years old, I'd be opening these envelopes that people would give in and I would see their checks with their name on them.

06:21.002 --> 06:24.086
At 12 years old, I knew what two thirds of the church gave financially.

06:24.666 --> 06:26.328
I don't think anybody thought that totally through.

06:30.052 --> 06:36.338
And I realized something that I've realized in my life again and again and again.

06:37.730 --> 06:43.800
that there is a correlation between the most generous people and the most content people.

06:44.822 --> 06:45.664
Not the wealthiest.

06:46.465 --> 06:48.268
It wasn't the wealthiest who were the most generous.

06:49.330 --> 06:55.120
But man, the people who were the most generous seemed to be the kind of people that you wanted to be like.

06:55.641 --> 06:58.706
It's something I've seen time and time again in my life.

06:59.138 --> 07:04.083
And it doesn't matter how much they were giving, you could just tell they were sacrificing.

07:04.103 --> 07:15.434
And it's not that these people didn't have hard times, but it was who they were in the midst of the hard times that inspired me because they had learned the lesson that this widow had learned.

07:16.775 --> 07:27.826
Solomon, who was the wisest person, scripture says, that ever lived and the wealthiest person that ever lived, he wrote this in Proverbs, he said this, give freely and become more wealthy.

07:28.354 --> 07:30.836
be stingy and lose everything.

07:31.958 --> 07:33.699
Give freely and become more wealthy.

07:33.739 --> 07:38.664
Now, he's not necessarily talking about financial wealth, but like, man, what kind of people do we want to be?

07:38.924 --> 07:40.466
We want to be generous people.

07:40.526 --> 07:47.153
And when we're generous and we have an abundance mentality and we see the world that way, it just changes how we see everything.

07:47.193 --> 07:48.834
It changes how we see relationships.

07:48.854 --> 07:50.736
It changes the openness of our heart.

07:50.976 --> 07:56.722
But when we're tight fisted, when it's all for us, it's about how we can get more

07:57.602 --> 08:00.085
There's something we lose even on the inside.

08:00.145 --> 08:08.336
There's something about greed or selfishness or everything's about me that we know at the end of the day does something that shrivels up our hearts.

08:09.757 --> 08:14.503
And there's something about generosity that unlocks something in our lives.

08:15.605 --> 08:20.952
See, when it comes to what God teaches about generosity, God doesn't want something from you.

08:21.052 --> 08:22.394
He wants something for you.

08:23.054 --> 08:25.938
Right, if God owns everything and made everything,

08:26.658 --> 08:29.802
He's not sitting there going, man, I'm really counting on your cash.

08:31.424 --> 08:35.089
Yeah, I'm really hoping you give because I'm gonna be in a tight jam.

08:37.052 --> 08:39.375
So why, why does he talk about generosity?

08:39.656 --> 08:41.458
Why does he encourage us in generosity?

08:41.699 --> 08:44.843
Because it's something that he wants for us.

08:46.064 --> 08:56.018
And I love this, Solomon wrote this Proverb in Proverbs 23, and I think it's one that's just really, really helpful to us in our culture today.

08:56.898 --> 08:58.902
The wisest person who ever lived, he said this.

08:59.343 --> 09:03.150
He said, don't wear yourself out trying to get rich.

09:04.052 --> 09:06.556
Be wise enough to know when to quit.

09:07.298 --> 09:11.786
Now, if you look at the transl, there's like a bunch of translations of this verse, I'll save you the time.

09:12.247 --> 09:14.973
The spirit of this passage is restraint.

09:15.734 --> 09:19.922
Some versions would say, be wise enough to know when to show restraint.

09:21.378 --> 09:27.764
He says, in the blink of an eye, wealth disappears, for it will sprout wings and fly away like an eagle.

09:28.485 --> 09:37.113
The idea of, hey, I understand that you wanna do well financially, but the idea of more and more and more is never gonna be enough.

09:37.834 --> 09:44.760
It doesn't matter how much you accumulate and how much you buy, there will be a day, you leave it all behind, right?

09:44.800 --> 09:48.724
There are no U-Halls behind herses, you've heard it before.

09:49.445 --> 09:51.026
You will leave it all behind.

09:51.490 --> 09:55.034
No, man, when it's wise enough to show some restraint.

09:55.375 --> 09:57.137
And can I tell you something about our culture?

09:57.657 --> 09:59.760
Our culture is not good at restraint.

10:01.462 --> 10:03.504
It's why we're all over leverage, right?

10:04.105 --> 10:05.366
It's why you're like, you know what?

10:06.007 --> 10:08.430
You were here last week and you're like, enough is enough.

10:09.872 --> 10:14.016
And then you're on Amazon and it said, you might also like.

10:16.980 --> 10:18.802
And you were like, hmm.

10:20.258 --> 10:28.086
I don't really need a carbon fiber pickleball racket, but we all have our thing.

10:28.106 --> 10:33.751
I don't really need another bag of chips, but we're not good at restraint.

10:33.931 --> 10:46.404
It's why our whole country is struggling with debt because we just leverage and we leverage and we leverage ourselves again and again because we don't understand the lesson that Solomon is giving us.

10:47.645 --> 10:48.786
Show restraint.

10:49.442 --> 10:52.046
and grow your heart.

10:52.066 --> 10:53.388
Where does your dollar go?

10:53.428 --> 10:54.490
Let's talk about restraint.

10:54.530 --> 10:55.571
Where does your dollar go?

10:55.952 --> 11:02.883
So I did a bunch of study, mostly with stats cans, some with the Fraser Institute, because I wanted to get an idea of this.

11:02.923 --> 11:06.048
So after tax, this is where your dollar goes.

11:06.068 --> 11:07.309
So this is a dollar.

11:08.031 --> 11:09.393
It's not very Canadian, I know.

11:10.194 --> 11:13.880
And what I want you to do is you got this bag of M&Ms this morning.

11:13.900 --> 11:15.122
I want you to actually take it out.

11:15.522 --> 11:18.066
And if you've eaten them all,

11:19.394 --> 11:20.815
You need to learn restraint.

11:23.378 --> 11:24.939
You've already learned the lesson.

11:24.959 --> 11:25.480
Take them out.

11:26.281 --> 11:29.704
And you've got 10 M&Ms there.

11:30.384 --> 11:32.226
And I want you to just lay them out on your lap.

11:33.487 --> 11:36.030
And if you're wearing your Gucci pants, just be careful.

11:37.992 --> 11:38.752
Lay out on your lap.

11:39.433 --> 11:41.595
And there's 10 M&Ms there.

11:42.156 --> 11:44.458
Three of those M&Ms are going to go to housing.

11:44.538 --> 11:48.882
So I want you to set aside three.

11:48.994 --> 11:51.156
M&Ms of every 10 are going to go to housing.

11:51.216 --> 11:52.978
Then, here's what's next.

11:53.799 --> 11:56.221
You've got food and auto.

11:57.382 --> 11:59.564
That's another three M&Ms.

11:59.584 --> 12:01.326
So food used to be about 10.

12:01.546 --> 12:02.587
Now it's about 15.

12:02.707 --> 12:06.791
If you've been to the grocery store, you know some of you have financed grapes and granola bars.

12:08.433 --> 12:09.434
And then here's your auto.

12:09.454 --> 12:17.522
That's likely your car, whether you purchased it or you've got a car fleece or whatever you've got.

12:18.818 --> 12:20.941
And so that's six M&M so far.

12:20.981 --> 12:21.763
You with me so far?

12:21.823 --> 12:25.869
Okay, because I'm not good at math, so I like it simple, okay?

12:26.350 --> 12:27.612
And here's what's left.

12:28.393 --> 12:33.081
You've got recreational, personal, that's your pickleball racket that you overspent on this week.

12:34.563 --> 12:35.184
That's one.

12:35.845 --> 12:37.788
House operations, that's one.

12:37.828 --> 12:41.214
That's your cleaning supplies, your furniture, your repairs, that's one.

12:42.015 --> 12:43.858
Then you've got debt or savings.

12:44.066 --> 12:46.490
7% and health and education.

12:46.510 --> 12:49.194
So this comes out to about 9.6 M&Ms.

12:49.895 --> 12:55.603
So if you want to bite one and a half and keep 0.4, put in your pocket for later, you can do that.

12:55.683 --> 12:59.109
But essentially, this is where the 10 M&Ms go.

12:59.209 --> 13:02.333
This is where the average Canadian dollar goes.

13:04.276 --> 13:07.421
And the question I have is, but what about God?

13:09.124 --> 13:12.228
Where does God end up on this list?

13:12.268 --> 13:13.330
Because this really,

13:13.954 --> 13:15.616
is all about me, isn't it?

13:17.578 --> 13:22.203
That often God gives us so much in our lives.

13:25.407 --> 13:28.630
And for us, so much of it is like, okay, well, that's all about me.

13:29.792 --> 13:30.813
I'm gonna have all of that.

13:31.353 --> 13:32.354
I'm gonna take all of that.

13:33.376 --> 13:34.697
You can eat your M&Ms if you want.

13:34.737 --> 13:35.278
You can eat them.

13:35.758 --> 13:36.759
Consume them, guys.

13:36.859 --> 13:38.661
So we're a consumer mentality here.

13:38.721 --> 13:39.322
No, I'm just kidding.

13:41.464 --> 13:42.866
But isn't that what we do?

13:43.938 --> 13:46.140
We end up consuming it all for ourselves.

13:46.160 --> 13:48.683
The average Canadian gives 1% to charity.

13:48.723 --> 13:51.526
The average American gives 2% by the way.

13:51.566 --> 13:57.392
And it's so important that we have an exercise like this.

13:57.512 --> 13:58.393
And the reason is this.

13:58.953 --> 14:02.437
How you handle your money dictates how you see the world.

14:03.818 --> 14:07.262
How you handle the money often dictates how you see God.

14:09.604 --> 14:11.666
See, when God looks at the

14:11.810 --> 14:13.332
finances that he's given you.

14:13.453 --> 14:18.661
It isn't about the amount in your account, but it's about the posture of your heart.

14:19.882 --> 14:21.625
It's not about how much money you have.

14:21.665 --> 14:23.448
It's not about how big your account is.

14:23.808 --> 14:27.895
Jesus doesn't go, oh man, look at how much money that person has.

14:28.175 --> 14:30.499
They must be more spiritual than this person.

14:30.719 --> 14:32.422
It's not about how much each of us has.

14:32.702 --> 14:37.810
It's about what is the posture of your heart with what you have.

14:41.026 --> 14:48.436
Scripture's very clear that when it comes to how we look at our finances, we've got to remember that everything we have comes from God.

14:49.378 --> 14:50.719
Everything we have comes from Him.

14:51.280 --> 14:55.887
It says in Psalm 24, it says this, the earth is the Lord's and everything in it.

14:56.547 --> 14:59.131
The world and all its people belong to Him.

15:00.353 --> 15:07.122
The car that I have, the house that I live in, the pickleball racket that I buy,

15:07.970 --> 15:09.431
All of this belongs to God.

15:09.552 --> 15:10.492
It's all his.

15:10.733 --> 15:15.357
You know, the finances that you make through your job, he gave you that skill set.

15:15.477 --> 15:16.698
He made you how you are.

15:16.739 --> 15:18.901
That's why you're so good at your job.

15:19.481 --> 15:22.264
That's why you've been given the business you've been given.

15:22.304 --> 15:25.407
That's why you've ended up in the area that you've ended up in.

15:27.229 --> 15:28.290
All of it comes from him.

15:28.310 --> 15:29.411
All of it is his.

15:29.771 --> 15:32.554
Everything we have is coming from him.

15:32.594 --> 15:34.876
It's all his.

15:35.457 --> 15:36.818
And it's all coming.

15:37.058 --> 15:38.500
from him again and again.

15:38.520 --> 15:46.552
In 1 Corinthians Paul says this, he says, you do not belong to yourself for you were bought with a high price.

15:47.894 --> 15:53.362
That if you are a follower of Jesus, Jesus gave his life on the cross for you and for me.

15:54.244 --> 15:56.868
He desperately wants to have a relationship with all of us.

15:57.228 --> 15:57.849
He bought us.

15:57.909 --> 16:01.254
He paid for our sins at the highest of prices.

16:03.177 --> 16:06.482
And we are stewards of what he gives us.

16:07.938 --> 16:16.807
Tim Keller wrote this book called Generous Justice, and he says this, a lack of generosity refuses to acknowledge that your assets are not really yours but God's.

16:20.170 --> 16:27.737
See, culture, culture teaches you to think like a consumer, but God asks you to be his money manager.

16:28.718 --> 16:31.581
Culture tells you more, more, more for you.

16:31.661 --> 16:33.223
You just take it all for yourself.

16:33.263 --> 16:35.024
You take as much as you can for yourself.

16:35.064 --> 16:36.786
You take it all for yourself.

16:37.314 --> 16:38.415
And this isn't enough.

16:38.495 --> 16:42.240
And if he gives you more, you just take, it's all yours.

16:42.320 --> 16:44.042
Just take it all for yourself, right?

16:47.445 --> 16:49.788
It's culture teaches you think like a consumer.

16:50.629 --> 16:51.550
I heard this joke once.

16:52.792 --> 16:54.253
It says, well, it's not really a joke.

16:55.114 --> 16:56.115
It's funny because it's true.

16:56.736 --> 17:03.744
When you're in the 20s and 30s, it says, you spend more than you have to impress people.

17:04.905 --> 17:05.586
And then,

17:05.954 --> 17:13.781
In your 30s and 40s, it says, you stop spending money to impress people because you're tired of all the payments you have to make.

17:14.502 --> 17:18.446
In your 50s and 60s, you realize nobody was watching in the first place.

17:19.387 --> 17:19.867
Isn't that true?

17:21.889 --> 17:24.812
The culture says consume, consume, consume.

17:25.612 --> 17:29.156
But God says, I've given you, we're all in different boat.

17:29.656 --> 17:30.637
We all have different amounts.

17:30.657 --> 17:32.779
We're all in different financial situations right now.

17:33.120 --> 17:35.762
But God is asking us all the same question.

17:36.866 --> 17:39.970
How are you managing what I've given you?

17:41.491 --> 17:44.695
In the Old Testament, you have the Israelite people.

17:44.995 --> 17:49.100
They've been wandering the desert, the wilderness for 40 years.

17:49.901 --> 17:54.767
And every day, God gives them this manna, this bread from heaven.

17:54.787 --> 17:57.450
They would have it for one day, and then it spoils, and then it's gone.

17:57.790 --> 18:01.114
And the next day, they would have to wait for men again, and it spoiled, and then it would be gone.

18:01.555 --> 18:04.498
And then after 40 years, they get to the Promised Land.

18:05.794 --> 18:08.558
And in Deuteronomy, this is what God says them.

18:09.099 --> 18:14.606
I mean, they're going into like, it's like just walking into a giant HGTV episode.

18:14.626 --> 18:19.754
Like everybody's house is done, perfect, all the food you need, everything you'll ever need.

18:19.794 --> 18:20.535
It's all here.

18:20.575 --> 18:22.157
The neighborhoods are beautiful.

18:22.557 --> 18:24.440
And he starts talking about the manna.

18:24.580 --> 18:27.965
And he says, he did all of this, gave you this manna every day.

18:27.985 --> 18:31.570
He did all this so you would never say to yourself,

18:31.682 --> 18:35.788
I have achieved this wealth with my own strength and my own energy.

18:36.789 --> 18:41.156
